🌵✨️ Saguaro Stars ✨️🌵
This is a shot from my March visit to see my folks in Arizona. I was there for eight days around the new moon and seven of the eight mornings were perfectly clear.

So I removed the tracker, lowered the tripod, spread the legs out,  stood blocking the wind, and shot several 15 second exposures to stack. Of the 20 I took nine were usuable 😁

On my last Milky Way outing I brought along my old Sony a6000 and the 18-55mm kit lens to see what I could get with just basic gear - no star tracker, no light pollution filter, and a cheap all-purpose lens.
This is 20 light frames stacked in Deep Sky Stacker with 20 flat frames and 20 bias frames. I also tried a version with 20 dark frames, but they actually degraded the final image. Dark frames cancel out noise generated by heat, but only if that heat is constant. A regular DSLR or mirrorless camera often varies in temperature too much for dark frames to be useful.
To demonstrate the difference stacking makes I've added versions with stacks of 1 exposure to 30 exposures (swipe). After about 15-20 the difference becomes very subtle so I usually stick to 20.

After learning from Nico Carver's (@nebulaphotosdotcom) latest YouTube video that you can download raw data from the JWST and process it yourself, well, I had to give it a try.
And this is the result. It's the "Pillars of Creation" in the Eagle Nebula. 
It's three monchrome images (that Nico prealigned and made available) taken with different wavelength filters combined into a false color image.
The wavelengths were 187nm, 335nm, and 444nm. The visible spectrum is about 380nm to 750nm. So I averaged the two ranges and transposed the images into the visible spectrum by adding 230nm to the values. In Siril's RGB Compositing (1.2.0 beta) you can enter the wavelength for each layer instead of picking a color. I went with 437nm, 565nm, and 694nm. Processing was fine tuned in Photoshop.
Wow, I'm a nerd!

More fun with space telescope data. This is my take on M51, the Whirlpool Galaxy.
The raw data is from the Hubble Legacy Archive. The data is saved as black and white images taken with filters that isolate different wavelengths of light. The various wavelengths can be assigned to red, green, and blue in different ways to create color images. In this case the data set was huge; the final image is about 85 megapixels (swipe for a full res detail crop)
For this one I used Pixel Math in Siril to combine infrared data associated with the element hydrogen (H) with data associated with oxygen (O) to create what's called the HOO palette. H is assigned to red and different mixes of O and H are assigned to green and blue.
For those that are curious the Pixel Math I used was:
Red: H
Green: O*.65 + H*.35
Blue: O*.8 + H*.2

On the edge of our neighborhood there's a fallow meadow surrounded by trees. It's an ideal spot for lightning bugs (and mosquitos 😝). 
My 50mm f/1.4 lens works great for lightning bugs/fireflies, but for this I tried a 35mm f/2.8. It's ok, but because it only captures 25% of the light the f/1.4 can capture  it requires longer shutter times and/or higher ISOs.
I shoot with a remote  in 'Aperture Priority' mode starting at ISO:100 and a 1 second shutter speed. As it gets darker the shutter speed gets longer. When it gets to 5 seconds, I up the ISO to 200. When the shutter gets to 5 seconds again, I up the ISO to 400. Rinse and repeat. You can just let the shutter speed get longer and longer, and stack the results for a still image but shorter shutter speeds let me also use the frames for a cumulative time lapse.

✨️ Milky Way PSA ✨️
On any clear night from September 5th through the 17th the Milky Way will be visible for at least an hour starting about 90 minutes after sunset. Here in Ohio sunsets are around 8 so astrodark starts about 9:30.
The 10th through the 15th are the optimal night with most time visible and the least moon pollution (is that a term? 🤔)
Look to the south-southwest to find the core. The higher you can be relative to the horizon the better, but sharp drops and darkness are a bad combo so be careful.
Wondering where to go? Checkout www.lightpolutionmap.info  Blue and green areas are good. Yellow is ok. Orange, red, and white are bad.
For astrocentric weather forecasts for your chosen location check out clearoutside.com

54,000 Times
Sometimes I caption my images here as more art than actual. This one is more actual than art 😁
While visiting Tucson last month I drove about an hour west to a truly dark sky area -  Bortle 2/1 (SQM of 21.92). I got there before the Moon had set so I did a test panorama while I waited and this is the result.
The brightness of sky stuff is described with magnitude numbers. It's a convoluted system that's been torn apart and duct taped back together many times over the last 150 years, but it's what we've got. 
The Moon has a magnitude of -10.79.  Antares, a bright star near the Milky Way core (seen from Earth) is a 1.05. The Moon is 54,000 times as bright as Antares! 
In less dark skies the Milky Way is already washed out by light pollution and a shot like this is nearly impossible. In a truly dark sky spot you can get both.
The dark sky and Moon also let me capture that bright area to the right of the Dark Horse Nebula and above the Moon called The Lens Flare Nebula 😏🤣
ISO:640 f/2.8 50mm 30 sec.
Two row, five column panorama
Sony A7RII + Rokkor 50mm f/1.4
